{"id":1269,"parent_id":0,"book_id":8,"content_id":1,"language_id":1,"display_order":1269,"title":"Zerubbabel","subtitle":"","short_title":"Zerubbabel","uri":"/scriptures/bd/zerubbabel","content":[["div",{"id":"t1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/zerubbabel.t1","order":".000.4061"},[".title","Zerubbabel"],["div",{"id":"p1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/zerubbabel.p1","order":".000.4062"},["i","Born in Babylon"],"(the name is Assyrian). Grandson of Jehoiachin, king of Judah, and son of Pedaiah (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/1-chr/3.16-19"},"1 Chr. 3:16–19"],"); in",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/ezra/3.2"},"Ezra 3:2"],"and elsewhere he is called “son of Shealtiel,” probably his nephew or legal heir. Zerubbabel was also known by the Persian name Sheshbazzar (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/ezra/1.8"},"Ezra 1:8"],", etc.). When Cyrus gave permission to the Jews to return to Palestine, Zerubbabel was appointed",["i","pekhah"],"or governor, as the representative of the Jewish royal house (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/ezra/1.8"},"Ezra 1:8"],"). He set up an altar in Jerusalem and rebuilt the temple (see",["i",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/bd/temple-of-zerubbabel"},"Temple of Zerubbabel"]],") (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/ezra/3.2,8"},"Ezra 3:2, 8"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/ezra/4.2-3"},"4:2–3"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/ezra/5.2"},"5:2"],"); being helped by Haggai (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/hag/1.1-14"},"Hag. 1:1–14"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/hag/2"},"2"],") and Zechariah (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/zech/4.6-10"},"Zech. 4:6–10"],"). In the New Testament he is called “Zorobabel.”"]]],"refs":null}
